The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, Oct. 11: The Life Insurance Corporation of India (LIC) has pumped in around Rs 90,000 crore into the markets, of which Rs 16,000 crore was invested in equities during the first-half of this fiscal, LIC executive director (investment operations) N. Mohan Raj said. We have made a total investment of over Rs 90,000 crore in various instruments of the markets till September-end, he said.                             
	 Mumbai, Oct. 11: Air India has selected global consultancy firms Booz Allen amp; Company and RothsChild to guide the national airline on its cost rationalisation and debt restructuring strategies. Air India CMD Arvind Jadhav is likely to hold a meeting with the senior management on the issue tomorrow.                            
	 New Delhi, Oct. 11: The government is expected to give over Rs 15,000 crore to around 10 public sector banks after Parliaments winter session as part of a recapitalisation exercise. According to initial estimates, the banks will require about Rs 15,000 crore for raising their capital adequacy ratios to over 12 per cent.                             
	 New Delhi, Oct. 11: Sugar output may rise seven per cent to 15.8 million tonnes in this season (October-September) on higher cane yield, a US department of agriculture report said. The production of the sweetener in India may go up from the last seasons (October 2008-September 2009) level of 14.7 million tonnes.                             
	 New Delhi, Oct. 11: Entrepreneurs in the micro, small and medium sector expect better sales in the remaining months of 2009-10 buoyed by the growth in turnover and order position in the second quarter of this fiscal, a survey by industry body CII said.                             
	 Calcutta, Oct. 11: Haldia Petrochemicals Ltd (HPL) has sought Rs 400 crore from a consortium of banks in the corporate debt restructuring cell to part finance the companys expansion project.                            
	 Mumbai, Oct. 11: Tyre manufacturers have hiked prices by 2-4 per cent from October 1 because of a rise in the prices of natural rubber, the key raw material, in the last five to six months.                                                                                                                           
